1 ISL Exercise 8.4.3 (10pts)

Consider the Gini index, classification error, and entropy in a simple classification setting with two classes. Create a single plot that displays each of these quantities as a function of \(\hat p_{m1}\). The x-axis should display \(\hat p_{m1}\), ranging from 0 to 1, and the \(y\)-axis should display the value of the Gini index, classification error, and entropy.

Hint: In a setting with two classes, \(\hat p_{m1}\) = 1 â \(\hat p_{m2}\). You could make this plot by hand, but it will be much easier to make in R.

Answer:

Create a data frame with \(\hat p_{m1}\) ranging from 0 to 1, and calculate the Gini index, classification error, and entropy.

library(ggplot2)
p <- seq(0, 1, 0.01)
df <- data.frame(
  p = p,
  gini = p * (1 - p) * 2,
  entropy = -(p * log(p) + (1 - p) * log(1 - p)),
  class_err = 1 - pmax(p, 1 - p)
) 
print(df, width = 200)

3 ISL Exercise 8.4.5 (10pts)

Suppose we produce ten bootstrapped samples from a data set containing red and green classes. We then apply a classification tree to each bootstrapped sample and, for a specific value of X, produce 10 estimates of \(P\)(Class is Red|X):

0.1, 0.15, 0.2, 0.2, 0.55, 0.6, 0.6, 0.65, 0.7, and 0.75.

There are two common ways to combine these results together into a single class prediction. One is the majority vote approach discussed in this chapter. The second approach is to classify based on the average probability. In this example, what is the final classification under each of these two approaches?

Answer:

Generate the data:

estimates <- c(0.1, 0.15, 0.2, 0.2, 0.55, 0.6, 0.6, 0.65, 0.7, 0.75)
print(estimates)
 [1] 0.10 0.15 0.20 0.20 0.55 0.60 0.60 0.65 0.70 0.75
num_estimates <- length(estimates)
cat('There are', num_estimates, 'estimates in total\n')
There are 10 estimates in total

Assuming a decision threshold probability of 0.5

p_threshold <- 0.5
numRed <- sum(estimates >= p_threshold)
numGreen <- sum(estimates < p_threshold)

For the majority vote approach:

cat('Using the majority vote approach:\n')
Using the majority vote approach:
cat('The number of votes for class Red =', numRed, '\n')
The number of votes for class Red = 6 
cat('The number of votes for class Green =', numGreen, '\n')
The number of votes for class Green = 4 
if (numRed >= numGreen) {
  cat('The assigned class is Red\n')
} else {
  cat('The assigned class is Green\n')
}
The assigned class is Red

For the average probability approach:

cat('Using the average vote approach:\n')
Using the average vote approach:
mean_estimate <- mean(estimates)
cat('The mean estimate is', mean_estimate, '\n')
The mean estimate is 0.45 
if (mean_estimate >= p_threshold) {
  cat('The assigned class is Red\n')
} else {
  cat('The assigned class is Green\n')
}
The assigned class is Green

Histogram with threshold, mean, and median lines:

hist(estimates, breaks = 10, main = "Histogram of Estimates", xlab = "Estimates", col = "lightblue")
abline(v = p_threshold, col = "black", lwd = 2)
abline(v = mean_estimate, col = "red", lwd = 2)
abline(v = median(estimates), col = "blue", lwd = 2)
legend("topright", 
       legend = c("Threshold", "Mean", "Median"), 
       fill = c("black", "red", "blue"))

Recipe:

tree_recipe <- 
  recipe(
    Sales ~ ., 
    data = Carseats_other
  ) %>%
  step_naomit(all_predictors()) %>%
  # # create traditional dummy variables (not necessary for random forest in R)
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors()) %>%
  # zero-variance filter
  step_zv(all_numeric_predictors()) %>% 
  # # center and scale numeric data (not necessary for random forest)
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors()) %>%
  # estimate the means and standard deviations
  prep(training = Carseats_other, retain = TRUE)
tree_recipe

Model:

classtree_mod <- decision_tree(
  cost_complexity = tune(),
  tree_depth = tune(),
  min_n = 5,
  mode = "classification",
  engine = "rpart"
  )

  add_recipe(tree_recipe) %>%
  add_model(classtree_mod)
